{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"b944134e-b5da-4898-b345-2a7b37c69752","content":"Use `dotnet watch test` — it re-runs tests automatically whenever you save a file. To focus on just the failing test:\n\n```\ndotnet watch test --filter \"RemoveStock_ExceedsAvailable_ThrowsException\"\n```\n\nWant me to start that watcher now? \n\n**Quick note on the bug itself:** `RemoveStock` never throws — it just subtracts, allowing negative stock. You'll need to add a guard like:\n\n```csharp\npublic void RemoveStock(string sku, int quantity)\n{\n    var current = _stock.GetValueOrDefault(sku);\n    if (quantity > current)\n        throw new InvalidOperationException(\"Insufficient stock\");\n    _stock[sku] = current - quantity;\n}\n```\n\nOnce the watcher is running, just save that fix and the test will re-run automatically.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"1942f5b7-fdc1-4642-91f5-f3f83099f0c6","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user wants to set up hot reload for iterating on the failing test. The project uses .NET 10 with MSTest and Microsoft.Testing.Platform runner. The `dotnet watch` command with `dotnet test` should work here. But more specifically, since .NET 8+, `dotnet test --hotreload` or `dotnet watch test` can be used.\n\nLet me suggest using `dotnet watch test` which will automatically re-run tests when files change. That's the simplest hot-reload workflow for tests.\n\nAlso, I can see the bug: `RemoveStock` doesn't throw an exception when the quantity exceeds what's available — it just subtracts, allowing negative stock. But the user asked about hot reload setup, not the fix itself.\n\n\nI'll show them how to run `dotnet watch test` with a filter for just the failing test so they can iterate quickly without running the entire suite each time.","outputTokens":407,"requestId":"3013:16EF68:449294E:4B63F58:6A031072"},"id":"ecbf3cc3-619e-4aa4-8586-edfa409b8240","timestamp":"2026-05-12T11:35:26.976Z","parentId":"061b8802-ad38-4d76-96a9-580bc5319